node.title: No new community COVID cases in Queensland, six in quarantine
node.alt: Queensland Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk speaking about COVID-19 on the Gold Coast
node.description: Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk says the cases in quarantine are not a risk to the community, but again urges people on the Gold Coast to get tested following a number of cases emerging there in recent days.
node.content: ["Queensland has recorded no new community cases of COVID-19 overnight.\u00a0", "Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk said there were six new cases detected in quarantine that were not considered to be a risk to the community.", "Ms Palaszczuk also welcomed the provisional approval of Pfizer vaccination for children aged five to 11.", "\"I welcome this news, I think it's good news,\" she said.", "\"Australia and Queensland have the capability of being the most vaccinated country in the world. I think that's tremendous.\"", "Queensland is expected to hit the 80 per cent double-vaccination mark for people aged 16 and over later this week.", "The Premier said\u00a0she would provide an update tomorrow on when borders were likely to fully reopen.", "Queensland's acting Chief Health Officer Peter Aitken said all of today's cases detected in quarantine were part of family groups.\u00a0", "\"The most important part is none of those people have been in the community and been infectious,\" Dr Aitken said.", "\"The other part of that good news is that there are no further cases linked to the Gold Coast.\"", "Authorities have been urging Gold Coast residents to get tested after a\u00a0man tested positive to COVID last week and it was revealed he had visited shops at Robina Town Centre while infectious.", "\"We still don't know at this stage where the initial acquisition of COVID came from so we still want people to come forward if they got symptoms and get tested at the Gold Coast,\" Dr Aitken said.", "\"This is just another reminder to us that particularly as we open our borders\u00a0there will be cases coming to Queensland \u2014 we know that and it's just a reminder that people do need to get vaccinated to protect themselves.", "\"The vaccine stops you from getting severe disease. It won't stop you from getting COVID and it's really important to remember we don't want Queenslanders to be in the hospital or intensive care.\""]
